Laser fields interacting with quantum wires 

Let us now consider a more complex situation in which a three dimensional
laser field hits the quantum wire polarized in such a way that it has a
vector field component along the wire. Since the work of Weyl,
one knows that matter may be coupled to light by means of a local gauge
transformation, which reflects itself in the usual minimal coupling
prescription, i.e. 
, with  being the vector gauge potential. The free Fermions in the
wire are then described by the Lagrangian density 
 
